1
00:00:00,090 --> 00:00:01,420
- In this lesson, we are going

2
00:00:01,420 --> 00:00:03,670
to talk about some agile focus areas.

3
00:00:03,670 --> 00:00:05,880
And these are things that are techniques,

4
00:00:05,880 --> 00:00:07,930
or procedures, or other areas

5
00:00:07,930 --> 00:00:10,570
that are focused specifically on agile.

6
00:00:10,570 --> 00:00:13,420
And you have to understand
these for the exam.

7
00:00:13,420 --> 00:00:15,271
The first one is the agilometer.

8
00:00:15,271 --> 00:00:18,750
The agilometer is a way of
assessing your agile environment

9
00:00:18,750 --> 00:00:20,920
in order to best tailor PRINCE2

10
00:00:20,920 --> 00:00:22,810
in the most effective way.

11
00:00:22,810 --> 00:00:24,690
This is going to highlight the risk areas

12
00:00:24,690 --> 00:00:26,550
that we have if we decide to use agile,

13
00:00:26,550 --> 00:00:29,600
and the benefit areas if
we are going to use agile.

14
00:00:29,600 --> 00:00:32,660
This helps the project board
make an informed decision

15
00:00:32,660 --> 00:00:36,510
when deciding exactly how
much agile we should use.

16
00:00:36,510 --> 00:00:39,040
This is performed on a pre-project basis,

17
00:00:39,040 --> 00:00:41,650
and it is repeated at each
of the stage boundaries.

18
00:00:41,650 --> 00:00:43,350
And the project manager is going to help

19
00:00:43,350 --> 00:00:45,284
to facilitate this assessment.

20
00:00:45,284 --> 00:00:47,880
You can see that there are six key areas

21
00:00:47,880 --> 00:00:49,200
that are going to be assessed.

22
00:00:49,200 --> 00:00:50,410
And we are going to grade them

23
00:00:50,410 --> 00:00:52,340
from one all the way up to five,

24
00:00:52,340 --> 00:00:55,580
with one being the lowest
and five being the highest.

25
00:00:55,580 --> 00:00:57,190
When we talk about one, this is going to

26
00:00:57,190 --> 00:00:58,910
to be things where we don't feel that

27
00:00:58,910 --> 00:01:02,000
the project environment
is well suited for agile

28
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:04,600
because of the way our
organization operates.

29
00:01:04,600 --> 00:01:07,440
So if I look at the flexibility
on what is delivered,

30
00:01:07,440 --> 00:01:09,530
how flexible is your organization

31
00:01:09,530 --> 00:01:11,570
with what that final product will be?

32
00:01:11,570 --> 00:01:13,210
If we have a lot of flexibility,

33
00:01:13,210 --> 00:01:15,250
that's going to be a five,
and it's going to be high,

34
00:01:15,250 --> 00:01:17,890
and very focused towards using agile.

35
00:01:17,890 --> 00:01:20,500
If it's one, and it has
to be a certain way,

36
00:01:20,500 --> 00:01:22,040
then we're not going to be as likely

37
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:23,830
to use agile in this scenario.

38
00:01:23,830 --> 00:01:26,170
The second one is level of collaboration.

39
00:01:26,170 --> 00:01:28,860
How much collaboration is
required on the project,

40
00:01:28,860 --> 00:01:30,590
and how well does our organization

41
00:01:30,590 --> 00:01:31,955
collaborate when it works?

42
00:01:31,955 --> 00:01:34,670
The third is ease of communication.

43
00:01:34,670 --> 00:01:36,760
Is it really easy for us to share things

44
00:01:36,760 --> 00:01:37,801
and talk with each other.

45
00:01:37,801 --> 00:01:41,570
For example, if we are all
working out of the same office,

46
00:01:41,570 --> 00:01:43,254
it's really easy for us
to get up from our desk,

47
00:01:43,254 --> 00:01:46,130
walk across the room,
and talk to somebody.

48
00:01:46,130 --> 00:01:47,850
But if our project team is going to

49
00:01:47,850 --> 00:01:50,383
be spread out across five
or six different locations,

50
00:01:50,383 --> 00:01:53,180
that's going to be more of a
challenge for communication.

51
00:01:53,180 --> 00:01:55,870
And so we might mark
it lower on that case.

52
00:01:55,870 --> 00:01:58,210
The next one is the
ability to work iteratively

53
00:01:58,210 --> 00:02:00,240
and develop incrementally.

54
00:02:00,240 --> 00:02:03,610
By doing this, can we work
in this spiral development,

55
00:02:03,610 --> 00:02:06,050
or do we need everything done at once

56
00:02:06,050 --> 00:02:08,090
for us to be able to deliver a product.

57
00:02:08,090 --> 00:02:10,470
For example, if I was
going to give you a car,

58
00:02:10,470 --> 00:02:12,180
and the customer required a car to drive

59
00:02:12,180 --> 00:02:13,860
from point a to point b,

60
00:02:13,860 --> 00:02:16,230
can you really work on that incrementally?

61
00:02:16,230 --> 00:02:19,310
Well some pieces you can,
but at the end of the day,

62
00:02:19,310 --> 00:02:21,600
the customer doesn't
want a half-finished car.

63
00:02:21,600 --> 00:02:23,090
They want a full car.

64
00:02:23,090 --> 00:02:25,990
And so being able to have
that full product means

65
00:02:25,990 --> 00:02:27,200
that we would be very low

66
00:02:27,200 --> 00:02:30,570
when we are measuring how agile we can be.

67
00:02:30,570 --> 00:02:32,850
Conversely, if I'm building
a software product,

68
00:02:32,850 --> 00:02:35,409
I can probably be very
high on the agile meter

69
00:02:35,409 --> 00:02:38,910
because I'm able to figure
out and put pieces of it

70
00:02:38,910 --> 00:02:42,670
and add functionality later
and very quickly and easily.

71
00:02:42,670 --> 00:02:44,210
Another good example of this is

72
00:02:44,210 --> 00:02:45,690
if I'm building a satellite.

73
00:02:45,690 --> 00:02:48,440
Once you launch that satellite
into orbit, it's up there.

74
00:02:48,440 --> 00:02:50,800
You can't go and add
another piece to it later.

75
00:02:50,800 --> 00:02:53,665
And so that is a very
low agile way of working.

76
00:02:53,665 --> 00:02:55,547
The fifth area we are
going to to consider is

77
00:02:55,547 --> 00:02:58,690
an anvantageous environmental conditions.

78
00:02:58,690 --> 00:03:00,180
Is our environment that we're going

79
00:03:00,180 --> 00:03:02,189
to be operating this project in culturally

80
00:03:02,189 --> 00:03:05,700
and available to work in an agile method?

81
00:03:05,700 --> 00:03:07,940
Some cultures are very agile focused,

82
00:03:07,940 --> 00:03:10,150
and others are very procedural.

83
00:03:10,150 --> 00:03:11,770
And based on that, you're
going to figure out

84
00:03:11,770 --> 00:03:13,900
if you are low or high in that area.

85
00:03:13,900 --> 00:03:16,460
And the final one, the
sixth and final one,

86
00:03:16,460 --> 00:03:18,870
is going to be the acceptance of agile.

87
00:03:18,870 --> 00:03:20,365
Do we accept agile as a way

88
00:03:20,365 --> 00:03:23,210
of practice inside our organization?

89
00:03:23,210 --> 00:03:24,920
If you're in a software
development company,

90
00:03:24,920 --> 00:03:26,870
you are probably very high on this.

91
00:03:26,870 --> 00:03:30,140
But if you're a commercial
builder you might be much lower.

92
00:03:30,140 --> 00:03:33,481
And so we have to decide how
accepting is the organization

93
00:03:33,481 --> 00:03:36,520
in terms of agile before
we can implement it.

94
00:03:36,520 --> 00:03:38,210
And now when we get all of these,

95
00:03:38,210 --> 00:03:39,750
we're going to mark them down on the chart

96
00:03:39,750 --> 00:03:41,140
of where we think we are.

97
00:03:41,140 --> 00:03:43,385
We're not going to average them.

98
00:03:43,385 --> 00:03:44,660
Each one is considered individually.

99
00:03:44,660 --> 00:03:45,870
But this is going to give us an idea

100
00:03:45,870 --> 00:03:50,150
of how agile we think we can
be inside of our environment.

101
00:03:50,150 --> 00:03:51,810
And if you're less agile, it doesn't mean

102
00:03:51,810 --> 00:03:53,951
that you can't use agile at all.

103
00:03:53,951 --> 00:03:55,700
It just means you're
going to have more control

104
00:03:55,700 --> 00:03:57,430
and more governance, and
tighter tolerances placed

105
00:03:57,430 --> 00:04:00,240
than if you were a highly
agile organization.

106
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,880
Now as I mentioned, when you grade these,

107
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:04,890
you're going to grade these pre-project.

108
00:04:04,890 --> 00:04:07,310
So all the back in starting up a project.

109
00:04:07,310 --> 00:04:09,480
That's going to say,
here's were we are today,

110
00:04:09,480 --> 00:04:12,300
but every time we hit stage
boundary, we're going to reassess.

111
00:04:12,300 --> 00:04:14,490
And so these can change over time.

112
00:04:14,490 --> 00:04:16,060
You may see that over the course

113
00:04:16,060 --> 00:04:17,960
of your project people start getting used

114
00:04:17,960 --> 00:04:19,590
to working in an agile way.

115
00:04:19,590 --> 00:04:21,800
And so these sliders might
move more towards the right,

116
00:04:21,800 --> 00:04:23,700
and more towards the high side.

117
00:04:23,700 --> 00:04:24,890
Now, once you've gone through

118
00:04:24,890 --> 00:04:27,033
and you've assessed
each of these six areas,

119
00:04:27,033 --> 00:04:29,860
you're going to be
considering them in isolation.

120
00:04:29,860 --> 00:04:31,240
We don't want to average them.

121
00:04:31,240 --> 00:04:32,420
We don't want to add them up.

122
00:04:32,420 --> 00:04:34,360
This isn't a sum total game.

123
00:04:34,360 --> 00:04:36,274
Instead we're looking at how agile we are

124
00:04:36,274 --> 00:04:38,433
in each of these six areas.

125
00:04:38,433 --> 00:04:40,140
This will give us a picture

126
00:04:40,140 --> 00:04:42,060
of how agile this project can be,

127
00:04:42,060 --> 00:04:44,101
or how little this project will be agile.

128
00:04:44,101 --> 00:04:47,921
The question is not yes or
no, should I use agile or not.

129
00:04:47,921 --> 00:04:51,390
The question is, how much
agile should I be using?

130
00:04:51,390 --> 00:04:53,076
If we're a highly agile organization,

131
00:04:53,076 --> 00:04:55,020
I'm going to give good tolerances

132
00:04:55,020 --> 00:04:56,940
and let my teams go out and build

133
00:04:56,940 --> 00:04:58,240
the thing they need to build.

134
00:04:58,240 --> 00:05:00,470
If we are less of an agile organization,

135
00:05:00,470 --> 00:05:02,090
I'm going to have tighter tolerances,

136
00:05:02,090 --> 00:05:04,390
and add more governances,
and more oversight

137
00:05:04,390 --> 00:05:06,330
as we go through the process.

138
00:05:06,330 --> 00:05:08,418
This is going to represent
our starting point.

139
00:05:08,418 --> 00:05:10,780
Now these assessments are done

140
00:05:10,780 --> 00:05:12,630
every time we hit a stage boundary.

141
00:05:12,630 --> 00:05:13,970
And so we are going to go back

142
00:05:13,970 --> 00:05:17,330
and look at where we are
today as an organization.

143
00:05:17,330 --> 00:05:18,850
And, when we hit that stage boundary,

144
00:05:18,850 --> 00:05:20,820
where we are at that point.

145
00:05:20,820 --> 00:05:23,490
As we see, these sliders may improve

146
00:05:23,490 --> 00:05:25,490
or they may go backwards.

147
00:05:25,490 --> 00:05:27,310
We're always trying to get more agile

148
00:05:27,310 --> 00:05:29,240
depending on the project we're working on.

149
00:05:29,240 --> 00:05:31,640
But in general, more agile
is going to be better

150
00:05:31,640 --> 00:05:33,660
because it's going to
help us reduce our cost,

151
00:05:33,660 --> 00:05:35,560
hit our time goals, and deliver a product

152
00:05:35,560 --> 00:05:36,833
that our customer wants.


